{{notability|Academics|date=May 2014}}
'''Anastasia Powell''' is a [[feminist]] [[criminologist]] at [[RMIT University]], [[Melbourne]], Australia. Powell gained her PhD in criminology from the [[University of Melbourne]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Powell |first1= Anastasia |title= Generation Y: Re-writing the Rules on Sex, Love and Consent |url= https://minerva-access.unimelb.edu.au/handle/11343/39369 |year= 2007 |publisher= [[VicHealth]] |location= Melbourne}}</ref> Her doctoral research was published in the 2010 book ''Sex, Power and Consent: Youth Culture and the Unwritten Rules'' by [[Cambridge University Press]].<ref>{{cite book |last1= Powell |first1= Anastasia |title= Sex, Power and Consent: Youth Culture and the Unwritten Rules |url= http://www.cambridge.org/au/academic/subjects/sociology/sociology-gender/sex-power-and-consent-youth-culture-and-unwritten-rules |year= 2010 |publisher= [[Cambridge University Press]] |location= Melbourne}}</ref> Powell's research specialises in policy and prevention concerning men's [[violence against women]], with a particular focus on [[sexual violence]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://junkee.com/sexual-assault-report-underreporting/117679|title=Experts Say #ChangeTheCourse Survey Underreported Sexual Assault|date=2017-08-11|work=Junkee|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/gender-culture-and-class-collude-in-violence-against-women-22957|title=Gender, culture and class collude in violence against women|last=Powell|first=Anastasia|work=The Conversation|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/national/2018/02/06/divorce-laws-outdated/|title='Outdated' wait for divorce 'can be deadly' {{!}} The New Daily|date=2018-02-06|work=The New Daily|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>

She is the author and co-author of several major Australian studies, including ''Australians' Attitudes to Violence Against Women: Findings from the 2013 National Community Attitudes to Violence Against Women Survey (NCAS)''<ref>{{cite book |last1= Powell |first1= Anastasia |title= Australians' Attitudes to Violence Against Women: Findings from the 2013 National Community Attitudes to Violence Against Women Survey (NCAS) |url= http://www.vichealth.vic.gov.au/~/media/ResourceCentre/PublicationsandResources/PVAW/NCAS/NCAS-StakeholderReport_2014.ashx |year= 2014 |publisher= [[VicHealth]] |location= Melbourne}}</ref> and ''More than Ready: Bystander Action to Prevent Violence Against Women in the Australian Community''<ref>{{cite book |last1= Powell |first1= Anastasia |title= More than ready: bystander action to prevent violence against women in the Victorian community |url= http://www.vichealth.vic.gov.au/Publications/Freedom-from-violence/Bystander-Research-Project.aspx |year= 2012 |publisher= [[VicHealth]] |location= Melbourne}}</ref> with the Victorian Health Promotion Foundation (VicHealth).

Powell is a co-founder of the [[Violence and Discrimination Against Women research network]] (VDAWnet) Australia, which seeks to promote research development and collaboration in areas including [[sexual violence]], [[sexual harassment]], [[intimate partner violence]], and [[sex-based discrimination]] against women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/national/act/sexual-violence-experts-join-on-university-sexual-assault-report-20170810-gxt21i.html|title=Sexual violence experts join on university sexual assault report|last=Baker|first=Emily|website=Canberra Times|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/courts-law/tradie-to-be-sentenced-after-intimate-photos-stolen-while-installing-the-nbn/news-story/6905c50a130ecbce9238fca456b1f653|title=These are the last sort of pictures you want stolen|work=NewsComAu|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> In addition to her scholarly contributions, Powell is regularly featured in and contributes to Australian news and media outlets,<ref>{{cite book |last1= HealthCanal |first1= |title= Report reveals poor attitudes to violence against women |url= http://www.healthcanal.com/public-health-safety/56166-report-reveals-poor-attitudes-to-violence-against-women.html |year= 2014 |publisher= |location= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1= MamaMia |first1= |title= When home-made porn is used as a weapon |url= http://www.mamamia.com.au/news/revenge-porn-laws/ |year= 2014 |publisher= |location= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1= ABC |first1= LifeMatters |title= Negotiating sexual consent |url= http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/negotiating-sexual-consent/3028978 |year= 2010 |publisher= |location= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1= ABC |first1= TheDrum |title= We're just not that into it |url= http://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2009-03-26/were-just-not-that-into-it/1631732 |year= 2009 |publisher= |location= }}</ref> raising the profile of issues including [[rape culture]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://theconversation.com/rape-culture-why-our-community-attitudes-to-sexual-violence-matter-31750| last1=Powell| first1=Anastasia| title=Rape culture: why our community attitudes to sexual violence matter| date=16 September 2014| publisher=The Conversation| accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/opinion/a-milliondollar-slap-in-the-face-for-students-and-sexual-assault-victims-20170403-gvcdzy.html|title=A million-dollar slap in the face for students and sexual assault victims|last=Funnell|first=Nina|date=2017-04-03|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> [[sexual assault]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://theconversation.com/justice-denied-the-neglect-of-sexual-assault-victims-with-a-disability-19294| last1=Powell| first1=Anastasia| title=Justice denied: The neglect of sexual assault victims with a disability| date=27 October 2013| publisher=The Conversation| accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> [[domestic violence]],<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://theconversation.com/gender-culture-and-class-collude-in-violence-against-women-22957| last1=Powell| first1=Anastasia| title=Gender, culture and class collude in violence against women| date=9 March 2014| publisher=The Conversation| accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> [[revenge porn]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theconversation.com/beyond-metoo-we-need-bystander-action-to-prevent-sexual-violence-91741|title=Beyond #MeToo, we need bystander action to prevent sexual violence|last=Powell|first=Anastasia|work=The Conversation|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en}}</ref> [[sexting]],<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://theconversation.com/not-just-safe-sext-victorian-parliamentary-law-reform-committee-calls-for-change-14804| last1=Powell| first1=Anastasia| title=Not just 'safe sext': Victorian parliamentary Law Reform Committee calls for change| date=31 May 2013| publisher=The Conversation| accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> and [[prostitution]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://theconversation.com/re-opening-the-prostitution-debate-its-time-to-make-women-safer-9854| last1=Powell| first1=Anastasia| title=Re-opening the prostitution debate: It's time to make women safer| date=1 October 2012| publisher=The Conversation| accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> A number of her public talks are available on her research blog.

