'''Lis Hartel''' (March 14, 1921 – February 12, 2009) was an equestrian from Denmark.<ref name=autogenerated5>[http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/15/local/me-passings15.S2 OBITUARIES / PASSINGS / Lis Hartel - Los Angeles Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.olympic.org/lis-hartel Lis HARTEL | Olympic Athlete | Helsinki 1952, Melbourne Stockholm 1956<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She was originally coached by her mother, Else Holst, but began to be coached by professional horseman Gunnar Andersen when she became nationally competitive.<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/lis-hartel-1.html Lis Hartel Bio, Stats, and Results | Olympics at Sports-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

She was the Danish [[dressage]] champion in 1943 and 1944.<ref name=autogenerated6>[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/sport/olympics/article773434.ece 100 greatest Olympic moments: Rider blazes trail for polio victims | The Sunday Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In September 1944 at age 23 she contracted [[polio]], which permanently paralyzed her below the knees, as well as affecting her arms and hands.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3nE0AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=%22lis+hartel%22+obituary&source=bl&ots=rGsHBZlUPG&sig=euPXGgIs83N8O7Q9wa0nYW-MGrE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=4jLmU6-xB4KbyATl-oCgDg&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22lis%20hartel%22%20obituary&f=false Fields of Courage: The Bravest Chapters in Sport - Max Davidson - Google Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated6 /> She was pregnant at the time, but had a healthy daughter.<ref name=autogenerated4>[http://www.britannica.com/olympics/reflections/article-9397307 Reflections on Glory<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Hartel was determined to continue her equestrian career despite medical advice otherwise, and in 1947 she finished second at the Scandinavian championships, although she had to be helped onto her horse when she rode.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/obituaries/articles/2009/02/14/lis_hartel_87_equestrian_won_silver_medals_despite_paralysis/ Lis Hartel, 87; equestrian won silver medals despite paralysis - The Boston Globe<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Dressage at the Olympics was open only to commissioned military officers until 1952, and in that year Hartel was one of the first women to compete against men in an equestrian sport at the Olympics.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Her silver medal in 1952 for Individual Dressage was the first by any woman in any individual sport when in direct competition with men at the Olympics, and she was also the Danish champion in dressage that year.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated6 /> She continued to be Danish champion in dressage in 1953, 1954, 1956 and 1959.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> In 1956 she also won another silver medal, this time at the 1956 Olympics in Melbourne, Australia (the Equestrian Games of those Olympics were held in Stockholm because of Australian quarantine laws for horses).<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/equestrian/1956/ 1956 Stockholm Equestrian Games | Olympics at Sports-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

After retiring from competitive riding, Hartel gave demonstrations, raising money for polio sufferers and supporting therapeutic riding for people with disabilities.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The Lis Hartel Foundation in the Netherlands, named after her, offers such riding opportunities.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated2 />

In 1992 Hartel was inducted into Denmark's Hall of Fame, and in 2005 she was named one of Denmark's top 10 athletes of all time.<ref name=autogenerated5 />

