'''Robert William Jensen''' (born July 14, 1958)<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Jensen, Robert, 1958- |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n95055442.html |publisher= Library of Congress | accessdate = November 9, 2015 |quote= (Robert Jensen; b. July 14, 1958) }}</ref> is a former professor of journalism from the [[University of Texas at Austin]]. From 1992 to 2018 he taught graduate and undergraduate courses in media law, ethics, and politics.

He has focused much of his work on the [[Feminist views on pornography#Radical feminist opposition|critique of pornography]] and of [[masculinity]], developed in his 2017 book, ''The End of Patriarchy: Radical Feminism for Men''. He also has written about [[white privilege]] and [[institutional racism]]. He also sits on the editorial board of the [[academic journal]] ''[[Sexualization, Media, and Society]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Editorial board: Sexualization, Media, and Society|url=https://uk.sagepub.com/en-gb/eur/sexualization-media-society/journal202355#editorial-board|publisher=[[Sage Publications|Sage]]|accessdate= 4 January 2016}}</ref>

==Early life==
Jensen grew up in [[Fargo, North Dakota|Fargo]], [[North Dakota]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | url = http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/freelance/whiteprivilege.htm | title = Robert W. Jensen: White Privilege | website = uts.cc.utexas.edu | publisher = [[Moody College of Communication|University of Texas at Austin College of Communication]] | date = July 19, 1998 | accessdate = April 24, 2011 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110612133025/http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/freelance/whiteprivilege.htm | archivedate = June 12, 2011 | df =  }}</ref>

== Education ==
In 1981, he received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from Moorhead State University (now [[Minnesota State University, Moorhead]]), and in 1985, he received a [[Master of Arts]] degree in journalism and public affairs from [[American University]]. In 1992 he completed his [[Ph.D.]] in media law and ethics in the School of Journalism and Mass Communication at the [[University of Minnesota]].

== Career and activism ==
Prior to his academic career, he worked as a reporter and copy editor for several newspapers, including the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' and the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]''.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | url = http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/vita.htm | title = Robert W. Jensen: Curriculum Vitae | website = uts.cc.utexas.edu | publisher = [[Moody College of Communication|University of Texas at Austin College of Communication]] | accessdate = April 24, 2011 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110515122022/http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/%7Erjensen/vita.htm | archivedate = May 15, 2011 | df =  }}</ref>

Jensen writes for popular media, both alternative and mainstream.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | url = http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/articles.html | title = Robert W. Jensen:  Articles | website = uts.cc.utexas.edu | publisher = [[Moody College of Communication|University of Texas at Austin College of Communication]] | accessdate = April 24, 2011 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110612110345/http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/articles.html | archivedate = June 12, 2011 | df =  }}</ref> His opinion and analytic pieces on such subjects as [[foreign policy]], politics, and race have appeared in papers around the U.S. He also is involved in a number of activist groups, including the Third Coast Activist Resource Center.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | title = Nuclear threats at home and abroad | url = http://www.thirdcoastactivist.org/nuclear-threats-at-home-and-abroad/ | website = thirdcoastactivist.org | publisher = Third Coast Activist Resource Center | accessdate = November 9, 2015 }}</ref>

==Controversy==

===9/11 opinion piece===
Jensen wrote an opinion piece for the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' on September 14, 2001, shortly after the [[September 11th terrorist attacks]].<ref name=Houston_Chronicle>{{cite news | last = Jensen | first = Robert | title = U.S. just as guilty of committing own violent acts | work = [[Houston Chronicle]] | publisher = [[Hearst Corporation]] | url = http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/freelance/attack1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151018091758/http://uts.cc.utexas.edu/~rjensen/freelance/attack1.htm | date = September 14, 2001 | archive-date = October 18, 2015 | access-date = November 9, 2015 }}</ref> In the piece, Jensen wrote that the September 11th terrorist attacks were "reprehensible and indefensible" but "no more despicable than the massive acts of terrorism – the deliberate killing of civilians for political purposes – that the U.S. government has committed during my lifetime."<ref name=Houston_Chronicle />

Jensen's piece drew both praise and criticism. Some individuals demanded that The University of Texas fire Jensen. In response, University of Texas President [[Larry Faulkner]] wrote in a letter to the editor published in the Houston Chronicle that he was "disgusted by Jensen's article" and called Jensen "a fountain of undiluted foolishness on issues of public policy."<ref>{{cite news | first = Lee | last = Nichols | title = War of Words | date = September 28, 2001 | url = http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2001-09-28/83161/ | work = [[The Austin Chronicle]] | publisher = Nick Barbaro | accessdate = November 23, 2013 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121104163401/http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2001-09-28/83161/ | archivedate=November 4, 2012 }}</ref>

=== Views on transgender ideology ===
In early July 2014, MonkeyWrench Books collective cut all ties with Jensen over his article reviewing two feminist books that critiqued transgenderism.<ref name=MonkeyWrench_Books>{{cite web | last = MonkeyWrench books collective | url = http://us7.campaign-archive1.com/?u=6cd8e997251fc0b0a88b19ea2&id=a48679cee3&e=1ca6c3321c | title = Smash the Cistem | website = us7.campaign-archive1.com |publisher=MonkeyWrench books collective | date = June 2014 | accessdate = July 26, 2014 }}</ref> These books were [[Sheila Jeffreys]]' ''Gender Hurts: A Feminist Analysis of the Politics of Transgenderism'' and [[Michael Schwalbe]]'s ''Manhood Acts: Gender and the Practices of Domination''. In the review published by ''Dissident Voice'', Jensen concluded that, "On the surface, transgenderism may seem to be a more revolutionary approach, but radical feminism offers a deeper critique of the domination/subordination dynamic at the heart of patriarchy and a more promising path to liberation"<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | title = Some basic propositions about sex, gender, and patriarchy | url = http://dissidentvoice.org/2014/06/some-basic-propositions-about-sex-gender-and-patriarchy/ | website = dissidentvoice.org | publisher = Dissident Voice | date = June 13, 2014 | access-date = November 9, 2015 }}</ref> which they felt "contributes to a dangerous culture of transphobia".<ref name=MonkeyWrench_Books /> In addition, Dexter M. Thomas wrote a rebuttal which was also published by ''Dissident Voice''.<ref>{{cite web | last = Thomas | first = Dexter M. | title = Gender and sexual diversity | url = http://dissidentvoice.org/2014/06/gender-and-sexual-diversity/ | website = dissidentvoice.org | publisher = Dissident Voice | date = June 21, 2014 | access-date = November 9, 2015 }}</ref> Jensen responded by writing a follow-up article which elaborated on his views on the ecological and social implications of the trans ideology.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert | title = Ecological and social implications of trans and climate change | url = http://dissidentvoice.org/2014/09/ecological-and-social-implications-of-trans-and-climate-change/ | website = dissidentvoice.org | publisher = Dissident Voice | date = September 12, 2014 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724062046/http://dissidentvoice.org:80/2014/09/ecological-and-social-implications-of-trans-and-climate-change/ |archive-date=2017-07-24 | access-date = November 9, 2015 }}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Jensen identifies as a radical Christian who rejects the supernatural claims of Christian orthodoxy.<ref>{{cite web | last = Jensen | first = Robert |url=http://killingthebuddha.com/mag/confession/the-inquisition/ | title = The Inquisition | website = Killingthebuddha.com | publisher = Killing the Buddha | date = June 5, 2009 | accessdate = April 24, 2011 }}</ref>  Jensen is married to musician [[Eliza Gilkyson]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Chotzinoff | first = Robin  | url = http://www.edibleaustin.com/index.php/people2/celebrities/936-eliza-gilkyson | title = Eliza Gilkyson | website = edibleaustin.com | publisher = Edible Austin | access-date = November 9, 2015 }}</ref>

